      "writtenOn": "2021-03-05T00:36:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Let\u0027s talk purpose of the package and its API.\n\nConsider tokenserver\u0027s bq/ package: it sorta generic in that it works against various tables with various schemas. Its users must therefore prepare proto-representation of rows on their own before calling \"LogToken\". Furthermore, it encapsulates *async* nature of requests by hiding TQ inside itself.\n\n\nI can think of 2 approaches: Generic and Run-specific.\n\nGeneric\n\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\nGiven `internal/bq`, I expected only generic BQ functionality, which should then provide just 3 APIs:\n   * API to instantiate prod Inserter, and perhaps install into context (which is typical approach we use in CV, but not used in Token Server)\n   * API to install fake inserter for use in tests.\n   * Either:\n     * SendRow(table, row) (**sync** call)\n     * AsyncSendRow(table,row) (puts TQ task)\n \n  -\u003e however, AsyncSendRow approach has downside in that TQ task will do anything else, e.g. we can\u0027t put a datastore entity.\n     -\u003e So, I think we should go with SendRow() sync API in this package.\n\nAnd I think it\u0027d be good to put all Run-specific code into run/... package.\nThe individual bq-export TQ tasks can be defined in Run package, as well.\n\nRun-Specific\n\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\nBasically, stick a combination of above into run/bq w/o generality.\n\n\n\nRun-specific approach is fine, but \na) we\u0027ll need to change destination table for BQ exports some day.\nb) I\u0027d like to emit non-Run BQ data, too.\nSo, I\u0027d vote for Generic approach since code-wise it\u0027s about the same amount.\n\n\nWDYT?",
